            <div type="translation">
                <!--bitte Übersetzung prüfen!-->
                <p>Μήτηρ Θεοῦ. / Θεοτόκε βοήθει Κωνσταντίνῳ πρωτοσπαθαρίῳ τῷ Μακρυγένῃ.</p>
                <p xml:lang="en">Mother of God. / Mother of God, help Konstantinos Makrygenes <hi rend="italic">protospatharios</hi>.</p>
                <p xml:lang="de">Muttergottes. / Gottesgebährerin, hilf Konstantinos Makrygenes <hi rend="italic">protospatharios</hi>.</p>
              </div>
            <div type="commentary" subtype="text">
                <p>The family name Μακρυγένης is attested only once in the sources and rather late, i.e. in the second half of the 15th century.[1] The family name Μακρογένης – written with an omicron – is, on the other hand, frequently attested.[2] The form Μακρυγένης – with an upsilon – could arguably be a variant of the more common family name. However, the hypothesis of it being a misspelled form of Μακρογένης, albeit unlikely, cannot entirely be ruled out. A man called Κωνσταντῖνος Μακρογένης is attested on a seal dating to the 12th century[3] which formerly belonged to the Collection of Georges Zacos.[4] Another seal belonging to a man with the same name and dating to the late 12th century was recently sold at auction:[5] the seal bears on the obverse an image of the Mother of God orans, and on the reverse a legend in four lines with an invocation to the Theotokos and the mention of the name and family name of the seal owner. Considering the date, the epigraphical and iconographic features, and the overall appearance of the three seals belonging to a Κωνσταντῖνος Μακρυγένης/Μακρογένης, we argue that the seals must have belonged to three different persons; a common identity among the three seal owners ought to be excluded. </p>
              </div>
            <div type="commentary" subtype="footnotes">
                <p xml:id="footnote-1">
                    [1]. <bibl><ptr target="PLP"/>, <citedRange unit="entry">no. 16434</citedRange></bibl>. A man called Μακρυγένης, attested in 1467 on the island of Crete, is mentioned in a letter written by John Plousiadenos and preserved in Bologna, Biblioteca Universitaria, 2378 (Diktyon 9728), ff. 26r-27r. See the edition of the document in: <bibl><ptr target="Laourdas1951"/>, <citedRange unit="page">p. 252-262</citedRange></bibl>. The letter does not specify whether Μακρυγένης is a first name, a family name or an epithet.
                  </p>
                  <p xml:id="footnote-2">
                      [2]. See, e.g., <bibl><ptr target="PBW"/>, <citedRange unit="entry"><ref target="http://pbw2016.kdl.kcl.ac.uk/person/Hilarion/107/">Hilarion no. 107</ref></citedRange> and <citedRange unit="entry"><ref target="http://pbw2016.kdl.kcl.ac.uk/person/Konstantinos/20382/">Konstantinos no. 20382</ref></citedRange></bibl>; <bibl><ptr target="PLP"/>, <citedRange unit="entry">nos. 16386-16391 + 92606</citedRange></bibl>. PLP also mentions a Στέφανος Μακρουγένης, attested in 1392/3 probably in Larissa (<bibl><ptr target="PLP"/>, <citedRange unit="entry">no. 16432</citedRange></bibl>). On the family name Μακρογένης/Μακρυγένης, see also <bibl><ptr target="Wassiliou-Seibt2011"/>, <citedRange unit="page">p. 272, no. 587</citedRange></bibl>.
                  </p>
                  <p xml:id="footnote-3">
                      [3]. See <bibl><ptr target="PBW"/>, <citedRange unit="entry"><ref target="http://pbw2016.kdl.kcl.ac.uk/person/Konstantinos/20382/">Konstantinos no. 20382</ref></citedRange></bibl> with its <bibl><ptr target="PBW"/>, <citedRange unit="entry"><ref target="http://pbw2016.kdl.kcl.ac.uk/boulloterion/3940/">Boulloterion no. 3940</ref></citedRange></bibl>.
                  </p>
                  <p xml:id="footnote-4">
                      <!--überarbeiten, wenn biblio in authority-->
                      [4]. See <!--Spink Auction 135. Byzantine Seals from the Collection of George Zacos III, London 1999, here p. 71, no. 312-->. The seal bears a metrical legend of six lines on the obverse and of five lines on the reverse.
                  </p>
                  <p xml:id="footnote-5">
                      [5]. Roma Numismatics, E-Sale 71, Lot 1421 (May 28, 2020). The seal now belongs to the Collection Sopracasa, no. 114.
                  </p>
              </div>
